<p><b>Mari</b> (modern <b>Tell Hariri</b>, <a href="Syria" title="Syria">Syria</a>) was an ancient <a href="Sumer" title="Sumer">Sumerian</a> and <a href="Amorite" title="Amorite">Amorite</a> city, located 11 kilometers north-west of the modern town of <a href="Abu_Kamal" title="Abu Kamal">Abu Kamal</a> on the western bank of <a href="Euphrates" title="Euphrates">Euphrates</a> river, some 120&#160;km southeast of <a href="Deir_ez-Zor" title="Deir ez-Zor">Deir ez-Zor</a>, <a href="Syria" title="Syria">Syria</a>. It is thought to have been inhabited since the <a href="5th_millennium_BC" title="5th millennium BC">5th millennium BC</a>, although it flourished with a series of superimposed palaces that spans a thousand years, from 2900 BC until 1759 BC, when it was sacked by <a href="Hammurabi" title="Hammurabi">Hammurabi</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
